  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Jamieson-Fausset-Brown Bible Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "14. kiss of charity—Ro 16:16, \"an holy kiss\": the token of love to God and the brethren. Love and holiness are inseparable. Compare the instance, Ac 20:37.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Peace—Peter's closing salutation; as Paul's is, \"Grace be with you,\" though he accompanies it with \"peace be to the brethren.\" \"Peace\" (flowing from salvation) was Christ's own salutation after the resurrection, and from Him Peter derives it.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "p",
        "class": "",
        "text": "be with you all that are in Christ Jesus—The oldest manuscripts omit \"Jesus.\" In Eph 6:24, addressed to the same region, the same limitation of the salutation occurs, whence, perhaps, Peter here adopts it. Contrast, \"Be with you all,\" Ro 16:24; 1Co 16:23.   ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
